  "prompt": "What is Nuclear Insurance Pool?",
  "response": "A Nuclear Insurance Pool is a collective of insurance companies that come together to provide coverage for nuclear risks, which are typically considered too large and complex for any single insurer to handle independently. This arrangement allows insurers to share the risk associated with providing insurance for nuclear facilities, such as power plants and research reactors, as well as for the transport and storage of nuclear materials.\n\nThe structure of a nuclear insurance pool allows for the distribution of potential losses among many different companies, thereby reducing the financial impact on any one insurer. These pools can insure against a range of liabilities, including property damage, third-party liability, and environmental damage arising from nuclear incidents.\n\nGiven the unique nature and potential severity of nuclear risks, insurance coverage often involves specialized policies and requires the expertise of underwriters who are experienced in dealing with nuclear energy and its associated hazards. Nuclear insurance pools exist in many countries, each operating under its national regulatory framework and often in cooperation with international nuclear insurance agencies.",
